  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is illegal in most jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained funds appear legitimate by disguising their true origin. This typically involves a series of transactions designed to obscure the source, ownership, or destination of the money. The exact definition and penalties for money laundering can vary by country, but it is universally considered a serious crime due to its association with other criminal activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism, fraud, and corruption.\n\nIn the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under several federal statutes, including the Bank Secrecy Act and the Money Laundering Control Act of 1986. Penalties for money laundering can include hefty fines, seizure of assets, and significant prison time.\n\nInternationally, efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Many countries have implemented AML laws and regulations in line with FATF recommendations to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.",
